observations.recommendation:
1.8 We recommended that Management strictly adhere to the prescribed policies and procedures in the effective control and accounting of supplies and materials and direct the:
a. City GSO to religiously prepare RIS for all issuances of supplies and materials, consolidate the aforementioned forms to be attached in the preparation of SSMI and subsequently submit the reports to the Accounting Unit for updating of its inventory records;
b. City Accountant to prepare the necessary JEVs to record actual issuances, based on the submitted SSMI, and reflect issuances to its respective inventory accounts;
c. City GSO and City Accountant to consistently reconcile actual inventories on stock and inventory accounting records in order to achieve the computation of accurate balances and the timely discovery and correction of errors; and
d. Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories on a semestral basis, and prepare and submit a report thereon.

We recommended that Management require the Project Engineer to:

submit an explanation why the Construction of the City Inn (Phase 10), Finishing Works (Phase 1) and Completion of the City Inn (Phase 13) were reported as 100% completed and Completion of the City Inn (Phase 14) as 85% completed even if they are not; 



cause the submission of the following documents for inspection purposes:

Duly signed Program of Works with Detailed Estimates for the Construction of the City Inn (Phase 10), Finishing Works (Phase 1) and Completion of the City Inn (Phase 13);
Bill of Quantities with Detailed Estimates for the Construction of the City Inn (Phase 10), Finishing Works (Phase 1) and Completion of the City Inn (Phase 13);
As built-plans for Phases with Back-up Computation of as built quantities, when applicable; 
Duly approved complete set of color-coded plan showing limit of work per phase; and
 Pictures during stages of implementation (before, during, after)

We likewise recommended that Management require the City Engineer to submit justification why there were procurements of construction materials considering the scarcity of laborers.

We recommended that Management instruct the City Accountant to:

set-up and/or record accounts payable with valid and complete supporting documents in adherence to Section 157 of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual, Volume I, Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and PPSAS 1;

present supporting documents of recorded year-end payables to establish their validity, propriety and existence;



revert prior years’ balances of accounts payable which have remained in the books of accounts for two years or more in line with the provision of Section 98 of PD No. 1445; and

revisit the existing process of procurement of the City Government starting from planning, budgeting and accounting and design an effective monitoring system with the objective of reflecting the true amount of Accounts Payable duly supported by proper and necessary documents.

We recommended that Management instruct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct the required physical count of inventory items every semester and to submit the RPCI to the Auditor’s Office with the certification and approval of the Agency Head not later than July 31 of the current year for the 1st semester and January 31 of the ensuing year for the 2nd semester;
City Accountant and CGSO to maintain supplies ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each inventory item/stock and to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records;
CHO Supply Officer to immediately prepare and submit to the CGSO the corresponding report of receipt and issuances of drugs and medicines, medical supplies and all the other items from the PDOHO and PHO;
CGSO to furnish a copy of the report of receipt and issuances to the City Accountant for proper and timely recording in the books of accounts; and
City Accountant to record issuance of inventory items held in stock based on SSMI and to correct the errors in order to accurately present the balances of the Inventory accounts.

Again, we recommended that Management:
a) Set-up and/or record accounts payable with valid and complete supporting documents in adherence to Section 157 of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual, Volume I, Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and PPSAS 1;
b) Present supporting documents of recorded year-end payables to establish their validity, propriety and existence;
c) Revert prior years’ balances of accounts payable which have remained in the books of accounts for two years or more in line with the provision of Section 98 of Presidential Decree No. 1445; and
d) Revisit the existing process of procurement of the City Government starting from planning, budgeting and accounting and design an effective monitoring system with the objective of reflecting the true amount of Accounts Payable duly supported by proper and necessary documents.

We recommended that the City Government:
a. Expedite the transfer of the acquired properties in the name of the City as required under Section 39(2) of Presidential Decree No. 1445;
b. Refrain from paying transactions without complete documentation to avoid suspensions/disallowances.

We recommended to Management the following:
a. Require the personnel in charge of the handling and maintenance of drugs and medicines and medical, dental and laboratory supplies in the City Health Office to maintain inventory stock cards and ensure that all issuances are duly accounted and properly documented;
b. Require the City Accountant to submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued with proof of actual usage and distribution of drugs and medicines and medical, dental and laboratory supplies in the City Health Office as basis in recording the expense account of these two inventory accounts.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
a. See to it that drugs and medicines being procured by the City are obtained from authorized suppliers, distributors and/or manufacturers as stated in their License to Operate and List of Sources;
b. Ensure the authenticity, safety and effectiveness and quality of procured drugs and medicines by requiring the supplier to submit together with their bids and/or quotations Certificate of Product Registration, Certificate of Good Manufacturing Practice and Batch Release Certificates from Bureau of Foods and Drugs Administration;
c. Adherence to the provisions of Administrative Order No. 43 series 1999, Administrative Order No. 47-A series of 2001 dated August 30, 2001 and Administrative Order No. 103 series 2002 issued by the Department of Health, Republic Act No. 3720 otherwise known as the Foods, Drugs and Devices and Cosmetics Act as amended by Executive Order No. 175, COA Circular 2012-001 and Presidential Decree No. 1445.

We have recommended management to ensure that:
a. Petty Cash Fund should only be used for cash payment of operating expenses in small amounts which could not be conveniently paid in checks or which require immediate payment;
b. The provisions of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act 9184 are strictly complied with, particularly the use of alternative modes of procurement;
c. The provisions of Administrative Order No. 17, series of 2011 in regard to procurement of common use supplies from the Procurement Service are adhered to;
d. The number of petty cash funds/petty cash custodians should be reduced and granted only to duly designated and properly bonded disbursing officer in the Treasury Office; and
e. Establishment, handling and utilization of the fund should comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 97-002 and the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for LGUs.

We recommended management the following:
Set-up and/or record accounts payable with valid and complete supporting documents in adherence to Section 46 of Presidential Decree No. 1177, Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and PPSAS 1;
Revert prior years’ balances of accounts payable which have remained in the books of accounts for two years or more in line with the provision of Section 98 of Presidential Decree No. 1445;
Continuous and thorough evaluation of the validity of recorded payables, particularly those pertaining to prior years, should be done in order to determine the immediate appropriate action and/ or necessary adjustments therewith; and
Revisit the existing process of procurement of the city government starting from planning, budgeting and accounting and design an effective monitoring system with the objective of reflecting the true amount of Accounts Payable duly supported by proper and necessary documents.

We recommended management:
That lump-sum appropriations be supported with detailed and/or specific programs, projects and activities in order to achieve transparency as well as effective and efficient planning and budgeting;
To observe strictly the provisions of Section 29(1), Article VI of the 1987 Constitution; Section 22 (c) of Republic Act No. 7160 and the Supreme Court ruling in Quisumbing, et al. vs. Garcia, G.R. No. 175527 as herein pointed out.

We recommended the following:
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to properly evaluate the completeness of Bidding Documents, Eligibility and Technical requirements and other documents before recommending the award of contracts to the City Mayor in line with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations ;
The City Government shall enter into contract with the winning bidder, provided, that all documentary requirements are complied with;
Management should submit the required documents; and
The City Accountant must require all pertinent documents before certifying the disbursement vouchers as to the completeness of supporting documents in line with Section 4(6) of P.D. 1445 to avoid doubts on the legality, validity and propriety of transactions.

We recommended management to:
Submit
authorization from the DILG or its appropriate bureau/ office/ unit on the conduct of benchmarking/ study tour/ lakbay-aral;
proof that the said benchmarking/ study tour/ lakbay-aral was included in Capacity Development agenda/ program of the city government;
Approved Itinerary of Travel;
Certificate of Travel Completed;
Plane Tickets/ Flight Itinerary Receipts/ Boarding Passes;
Certificate of Appearance/ Attendance;
explanation/ justification as to why leaves of absence had to be filed in the conduct of benchmarking/ study tour/ lakbay-aral, the same being an official activity of an LGU;
explanation/ justification as to why the above-mentioned three (3) personnel received their own share from the award despite their non-participation to the said activity; and
Strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of PD No. 1445, RA 7160 and DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular NO. 02 dated September 23, 2016.

We recommended management the following:
The Special Education Fund and Trust Fund should not be invested in High Yield Savings Account in line with the provisions of Section 21 and 22 of COA Circular No. 92-382 dated July 3, 1992;
The City Government must utilize the Special Education Fund and Trust Fund in accordance with the priority/specific programs and projects they have been intended for;
Secure prior authority from the Sanggunian Panlungsod before investing idle funds in the General Fund under time deposit accounts in accordance with Section 21 of COA Circular No. 92-382; and
Conduct investigation and if warranted, file appropriate charges against responsible officers and/or personnel.

We recommended and management agreed on the following:
Conduct the necessary field surveys and investigations in the detailed engineering during the planning phase;
Carefully study/ evaluate the site condition in the preparation of accurate design plans, technical specifications, quantity and cost estimates and program of work to minimize if not totally eradicate work suspensions that may cause delay in the completion of projects;
Propose and implement projects in an efficient and effective manner in pursuance of Section 2 of P.D. No. 1445 to avoid loss or wastage of government funds and property.

We recommended management to:
submit the documents mentioned in items a to m above in line with Section 53 of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act No. 9184 and Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445;
distribute what had been intended for the thirteen (13) recipient-barangays in accordance with the purpose of the transaction to avoid disallowance of the same;
refrain from making recipients/beneficiaries of programs and/or projects sign blank forms indicating receipt thereof; and
strictly abide by the guidelines for the prevention of irregular expenditures laid down in COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012 as well as the provision of Section 2, PD No. 1445.
